<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,258,1039]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,510,535]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">Description</emphasis>
. Vertex yellow marked with dark-brown on posterior margin and between ocelli. Forewing basally yellow variably tinged with green; distal two-thirds of corium and tip of clavus, pale-brown. Face with postclypeus yellowish-orange with a dark-brown pit in front of tylus; anteclypeus yellowish-orange with dark-brown tip. Rostrum and antennae, dark-brown. Pronotum yellow tinged with green posteriorly with a transverse line between anterior and median third and posterior margin, dark brown. Mesothorax dark brown. Legs yellow with proximal and distal area of tibia and tarsi, dark brown. Abdomen yellowish-brown with the anterior margin of segments dark-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,258,1039]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
Male pygofer without latero-posterior lobe (
<figureCitation box="[649,731,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1804]" captionTargetBox="[155,1427,260,1744]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,254,1760]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 17. Monecphora species, dorsal habitus and genitalia. 10 – 14. Monecphora machadoi sp. nov. (male paratype); 10. dorsal habitus; 11. male pygofer and subgenital plate, lateral view; 12. paramere, external lateral view; 13. aedeagus, lateral view; 14. aedeagus, posterior view; 15. M. nigritarsis; 16. M. semilutea; 17. M. sipolisi. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/255189/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
Fig. 
<number box="[702,731,763,787]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
). Parameres in lateral view with base of apophysis evenly and shallowly convex dorsally, ventral margin subapically abruptly narrowed tooth-like with a downwardly directed apical spine (
<figureCitation box="[300,384,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1804]" captionTargetBox="[155,1427,260,1744]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,254,1760]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 17. Monecphora species, dorsal habitus and genitalia. 10 – 14. Monecphora machadoi sp. nov. (male paratype); 10. dorsal habitus; 11. male pygofer and subgenital plate, lateral view; 12. paramere, external lateral view; 13. aedeagus, lateral view; 14. aedeagus, posterior view; 15. M. nigritarsis; 16. M. semilutea; 17. M. sipolisi. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/255189/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
Fig. 
<number box="[353,384,835,859]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal shaft with basal two thirds straight, thereafter with large apical angled flange-like expansion on each side, without processes (
<figureCitation box="[638,769,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1804]" captionTargetBox="[155,1427,260,1744]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,254,1760]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 17. Monecphora species, dorsal habitus and genitalia. 10 – 14. Monecphora machadoi sp. nov. (male paratype); 10. dorsal habitus; 11. male pygofer and subgenital plate, lateral view; 12. paramere, external lateral view; 13. aedeagus, lateral view; 14. aedeagus, posterior view; 15. M. nigritarsis; 16. M. semilutea; 17. M. sipolisi. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/255189/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
Figs 
<number box="[695,769,871,895]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149" value="13.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="13.0">13–14</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor with basal processes small and spoon-shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="149" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,258,1039]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,906,931]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is in honor of Angelo B. M. Machado the influential Brazilian researcher and entomologist, on the occasion of his 
<number box="[562,589,942,967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149" value="80.0">80</number>
th birthday.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="149" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,258,1039]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,978,1003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="149">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species can be distinguished by its distinctive color pattern and aedeagal shaft with large apical expansion on each side, without apical medial spinose process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
